definition.value: This is an AE which is dental pain which is sharp in character and of short duration, arising from exposed dentin surfaces in response to stimuli, typically thermal, evaporative, tactile, osmotic, chemical or electrical; and which cannot be ascribed to any other dental disease.
This is an AE which is the complete displacement of a tooth from its socket in alveolar bone owing to trauma.
This is an AE which is the horizontal or vertical displacement of a tooth beyond its normal physiological boundaries around the gingival area, i.e. the medical term for a loose tooth.
This is an AE which is one that fails to erupt into the dental arch within the expected developmental window.
This is an AE which is a type of tissue death caused by a lack of blood supply occured on dental.
This is an AE which is inflammation of dental pulp tissue.
This is an AE which is the process of lightening the color of human teeth.
This is an AE which consist of the mucosal tissue that lies over the mandible and maxilla inside the mouth and feel it discomfortable.
This is an AE which is a non-destructive disease that causes inflammation of the gums.
This is an AE which is an increase in the size of the gingiva (gums).
This is an AE which is the term given to any disorder primarily affecting the gingiva.
This is an AE which is a discontinuity or break in gingival membrane that impedes normal function of the affected organ.
This is an AE which is a type of cysts of the jaws that originates from the dental lamina and is found in the mouth parts.

This is an AE which is a small pocket of body fluid (lymph, serum, plasma, blood, or pus) within the upper layers of the gingival  skin, usually caused by forceful rubbing (friction), burning, freezing, chemical exposure or infection.
This is an AE which is a gingival sensation that causes the desire or reflex to scratch.
This is an AE which is the build-up of fluid in the gingival tissue.
This is an AE which is the exposure in the roots of the teeth caused by a loss of gum tissue and/or retraction of the gingival margin from the crown of the teeth.
This is an AE which is a non-destructive disease that causes inflammation of the gums.
This is an AE which is a typical adverse reaction of certain drugs (phenytoin, calcium antagonists and cyclosporine).
This is an AE which is a viral disease that causes inflammation of the brain in humans and other mammals.
This is an AE which is a visible body part at the mouth of humans and it is discolouration.
This is an AE which involves the removal of the oldest dead skin cells from the lip skin's surface.
This is an AE which is blood escaping from the circulatory system from damaged lip blood vessels.
This is an AE which refers constant licking of the lips causes drying and irritation, and eventually the mucosa splits or cracks.
This is an AE which is an ulcer that occurs on the mucous membrane of the oral cavity.

This is an AE which is a small pocket of body fluid (lymph, serum, plasma, blood, or pus) within the upper layers of the    lip skin, usually caused by forceful rubbing (friction), burning, freezing, chemical exposure or infection.

This is an AE which is the process by which an infant's first teeth (the deciduous teeth, often called "baby teeth" or "milk teeth") sequentially appear by emerging through the gums, typically arriving in pairs.

This is an AE which is a small pocket of body fluid (lymph, serum, plasma, blood, or pus) within the upper layers of the    lip skin, usually caused by forceful rubbing (friction), burning, freezing, chemical exposure or infection.
This is an AE which is inflammation of the mouth and lips and is  allergic.

This is an AE which is a common type of skin rash. Symptoms include multiple small (1–2 mm) bumps and blisters sometimes with background redness and scale, localized to the skin around the mouth and nostrils.

This is an AE which is the flow of saliva outside the mouth. Drooling can be caused by excess production of saliva, inability to retain saliva within the mouth (incontinence of saliva), or problems with swallowing (dysphagia or odynophagia).
This is an AE which is glossitis which manifests with hyperplastic (enlarged) fungiform papillae, giving the appearance of a strawberry.
This is an AE which is considered as a possible clinical finding of obstructive sleep apnoea (OSA).
This is an AE which is a common zoological behavior involving the active, rapid closing of the jaw around an object.
This is an AE which is also an age appropriate behavior and reaction for human children 30 months and younger.
This is an AE which may occur both in seizures and in psychogenic non-epileptic events (PNEEs).
This is an AE which is the increase in the volume of mucosal  tissue due to the enlargement of its component cells.
This is an AE which is a membrane that lines various cavities in the body and covers the surface of internal organs and it is dryness.
This is an AE which is a colored material on the mucosal that is completely or nearly insoluble in water.
This is an AE which is an exudate of inflamed mucous membranes in one of the airways or cavities of the body,usually with reference to the throat and paranasal sinuses.
This is an AE which is a burning sensation in the mouth with no underlying known dental or medical cause.
This is an AE which is inflammation of one or both corners of the mouth.
This is an AE which is a mode of keratinization characterized by the retention of nuclei in the stratum corneum.
This is an AE which is excessive teeth grinding or jaw clenching.
This is an AE which is a membrane that lines various cavities in the body and covers the surface of internal organs and it is discolouration.
This is an AE which refers a supramolecular assembly of lipid molecules, like a cell membrane.
This is an AE which is a misalignment or incorrect relation between the teeth of the upper and lower dental arches when they approach each other as the jaws close.
This is an AE which is one of the criteria for the diagnosis of idiopathic Parkinson disease and is often an early sign of the disease.
This is an AE which is inflammation of the alveolar bone (i.e., the alveolar process of the maxilla or mandible).
This is an AE which is a cellular aggregation seen in a developing tooth and it lies above the dental papilla.
